rComments: I took his cmps 115 class in last quarter. He is a nice guy but his lecture is so terrible. His deep and unemotional tune will make you sleep. He always showed up later for 10-20 minutes in a 1:45 hours lecture. During his lecture, he only pay attention on his PPT and no much eye contact with students.

Worst professor I've ever had. Lectures were so useless that by the end of the quarter 13 out of 100+ students were showing up. Lectures using the book tutorials, which you could easily do at home, and messes them up. Long silences in lectures. Rarely answers class forum questions. Gets angry and makes uncomfortable comments. DO NOT TAKE THIS CLASS
If you plan on taking this guy's class, save yourself the pain and just don't. kay?

It is true what everyone else said about him. It wasn't an easy quarter for me because of the uncertainties of the class.  Was his first time teaching the class and I can see him getting better. Very nice guy who took feedbacks from his students and tried to make the class better. He was very helpful and fun to talk with during his office hours.

Richard is a nice guy, unfortunately that doesn't help students out much when we don't learn anything in his class. He reads of incredibly difficult to understand slides, the book is very challenging to read as well, and he explains a lot of concepts that are best demonstrated on the board/overhead. His office hours will save you points, so go.

Jullig puts no effort into teaching. He shows up late to class, he does not respond to emails or posts to the class forum, and he reads verbatim from slides written by other lecturers. His tests are difficult for the wrong reasons. His poor teaching ruins an otherwise interesting course.
Out of touch with the students.

Attendance slowly dropped to around 15-20 students attending class daily while there are 90+ enrolled. He changes up the sylabus and doesn't give a clear grading scale. He tells students to ask questions on the online forum, but doesn't answer them. Easy class but horrible professor.

Has no idea how to teach, expects everyone to magically understand everything he tries to explain. Midterm was every college stereotypical nightmare you can imagine. 10 page long, little time, and you'd need to decode the questions first before even trying to answer. Gave no study direction except "Study everything!" to boot.

Horrible disorganized. It's week 7 and we've had a written homework assignment and a midterm (no programs). Neither had anything to do with the lecture. Lectures are long and monotonous; he downloaded his slides from some random online source and doesn't appear to have read them before class. Everybody is failing right now and the TAs are at loss.

Completely unclear. Horrible lecturer. Not engaging at all. He mumbles, he's vague, and sometimes it seems like he doesn't even know what his own slides mean. We never got a syllabus. Completely disorganized. He doesn't really seem to care a lot about teaching this class. Be prepared to rely completely on outside sources to help you pass.

Doesn't have a syllabus or website. Doesn't write notes during class until 3 weeks in. Reads from lecture slides, but takes about 5 minutes to read the slide in silence and then tries explaining while stumbling over his words, making his train of thought difficult to follow. Scarce examples, just basic algorithms on lecture slides.
